gm-method: a single non-ASCII decorative glyph sighting triggers a full-tree sweep. Exempt categories that survive the sweep: frozen CHANGELOG/git-log entries (em-dashes, arrows in past entries), code operators (=>, ??, ?.), and intentional product icon glyphs in dedicated icon fields (e.g. a YAML 'glyph:' key holding ▣/★/◐ as iconographic content, not prose). Convert everything else: arrow->'->', bullet/middot/'·'->'-', check/cross->'[x]'/'[ ]' or done/fail, '≥'->'>='. When the sweep touches client-side files (.html/.css/.js/.mjs loaded by a browser entry), each edit needs a SAME-TURN browser witness: serve the static dir on a local port, page.goto it, page.evaluate that document.body.innerText has zero forbidden glyphs AND fetch the raw source files to assert the glyph is gone at source, then transition only after the witness response shows clean. Without the paired browser dispatch, transition-to-EMIT/COMPLETE refuses with deviation.client-edit-no-witness.